node.text:
First time back in the Colorado mountains since dreaming of them from space.

Learning trail running to explore wild places and loving the challenge of a new sport to train with friends!

node.text:
Back to your other happy place! 

Great to train with you in your first time back in the T-38 jet simulator since you got back from space, @astrovicglover! Had to sport my Crew-1 pride in your honor. Look forward to real training flights soon too…hopefully with fewer jet malfunctions!

node.text:
What’s the view from the back seat of the T-38? 

Check it out in the reflection in my visor.

Great training flights this week in the NASA jet that we use to hone our skills reacting to fast problems with crew coordination!

node.text:
There’s a new solar array in town.

And you can watch it getting installed tomorrow on a spacewalk starting at 8am EDT. It’s a bold one, with two astronauts manually doing the job.

The new arrays will provide more power to the station to keep the operations and science always growing!

Check out the NASA app or link in bio.

node.text:
Exploring surf spots seen from space! 

Incredible feeling being in the waves at places I scouted from the @iss. This time it was the south of #Nicaragua, surfing Playa Hermosa, Maderas and Remanso. All even more beautiful in person.

#swellfromspace #SanJuanDelSur

Photo cred @erickbarboza.sjds

node.text:
Moon rocket main stage! 

Open the door on the giant rocket assembly building at @nasakennedy and on the other side is this breathtaking symbol of humanity’s love of exploration. It’s getting ready to attach to the powerful boosters that will make up the @nasaartemis Space Launch System rocket.

node.text: There’s about to be another star in the sky! @Boeing Starliner, that is. Soon to rocket astronauts to the @ISS and another partner in exploration that I was lucky to tour @NASAKennedy.

node.text:
Small capsule, big cosmos. 

Flying between the Earth and the @iss is one of the most dynamic yet peaceful parts of a mission. 

The past month, four capsules ferried astronauts on that journey, the last of which is a landing tonight, with splashdown at 2:56 am EDT that you can watch on NASA TV sources!

Photo taken of the approach of the Crew-2 Dragon capsule by @astrovicglover
